WEBVTT

00:16.265 --> 00:18.143
(thunder rumbling)

00:29.696 --> 00:31.031
(rain pouring)

00:34.952 --> 00:35.911
(wind blowing)

00:39.206 --> 00:40.165
(melodic whistling)

00:42.709 --> 00:44.378
(water lapping)

01:12.948 --> 01:14.575
(ship motor chugging loudly)

01:14.575 --> 01:15.784
(whistling grows louder)

01:21.373 --> 01:22.749
(children laughing)

01:22.749 --> 01:24.293
BOY: Last one there
goes to prison!

01:24.293 --> 01:25.794
GIRL: Wait, that's not fair.
Wait for me!

01:25.794 --> 01:27.462
GUEST: I said if you want to
see a clattering engine,

01:27.462 --> 01:29.464
stop by the Commons
on the first Friday
of the month.

01:29.464 --> 01:31.383
(dog barking)

01:31.758 --> 01:33.176
WOMAN: What do you
think is?

01:33.176 --> 01:34.845
MAN 1: Might just be a drill.

01:34.845 --> 01:36.430
-MAN 2: Very strange,
don't you think?
-MAN 3: Haven't you heard?

01:36.555 --> 01:37.681
-MAN 2: Heard what?

01:37.681 --> 01:38.890
-MAN 4: A rupture of some sort
in the engine.

01:38.890 --> 01:40.100
Oh, here comes someone.

01:40.100 --> 01:41.727
Excuse me,
where do you think he's going?

01:41.727 --> 01:42.769
MAN: (calls) Hello?

01:42.769 --> 01:44.021
(whistling continues)

01:54.865 --> 01:56.533
CREW MEMBER:
Take one, keep moving please.

01:56.950 --> 01:58.619
Take one.

01:58.619 --> 01:59.953
-GUEST: Did you say this way?
-CREW: Everything will be fine.

01:59.953 --> 02:01.205
CREW MEMBER:
Upstairs and turn left.

02:01.496 --> 02:02.748
MAN: I don't like this madness.

02:02.998 --> 02:05.584
-WOMAN: Are we sinking?
-CREW MEMBER: No.
Upstairs, turn left.

02:05.584 --> 02:06.627
Everything will be fine.

02:06.627 --> 02:08.211
Just continue upstairs,
please.

02:08.211 --> 02:09.420
Keep moving, please.

02:09.922 --> 02:11.423
(bell ringing)
Sir, keep moving, please.

02:11.423 --> 02:12.841
(door opens)
There you go, Sir.

02:12.841 --> 02:14.760
GUEST: Are there at least enough
lifeboats this time?

02:14.760 --> 02:16.428
CREW MEMBER:
Keep calm, go upstairs please.

02:16.428 --> 02:18.096
(whistling continues)

02:28.774 --> 02:30.192
PORTER: Hello?

02:33.904 --> 02:35.364
Mrs Ratch?

02:39.117 --> 02:41.537
(footsteps echoing)
(whistling continues)

02:41.537 --> 02:42.621
(bell ringing continuously)

02:42.621 --> 02:48.877
(ominous music)

02:48.877 --> 02:50.838
GIBSON: The porter found her
twenty minutes ago.

02:51.171 --> 02:52.214
CARRADINE: And?

02:52.339 --> 02:54.216
GIBSON: Apparently, her husband
used an axe.

02:54.258 --> 02:55.716
CARRADINE: Oh my God.

02:55.926 --> 02:58.762
GIBSON: The lunatic
hasn't stopped
whistling since he got here.

02:59.763 --> 03:01.223
CARRADINE: The little girl?

03:01.223 --> 03:02.558
GIBSON: We're still looking.

03:02.558 --> 03:03.725
(door opens)

03:04.476 --> 03:06.186
(jewellery box music tinkling)

03:07.104 --> 03:08.772
(glass crunching)

03:10.315 --> 03:11.733
(tense music)

03:21.076 --> 03:24.704
♪London Bridge is
falling down

03:25.204 --> 03:27.040
♪Falling down♪
(dog barking)

03:27.249 --> 03:29.293
♪Falling down♪

03:29.293 --> 03:32.588
♪London Bridge is falling down♪
(whistling)

03:32.588 --> 03:36.425
(tap dance shoes stepping)
My fair lady...

03:36.425 --> 03:37.968
(metal banging)

03:39.970 --> 03:41.263
(footsteps)
(whistling continues)

03:47.769 --> 03:50.939
(spurs banging wooden box)
(whistling getting louder)

03:56.278 --> 03:59.323
JACKIE: Daddy? Is that you?

04:00.073 --> 04:01.700
(creaking)

04:02.743 --> 04:04.161
DAVID: In the flesh.

04:06.163 --> 04:08.373
JACKIE: (upset) Mum...mum's
hurt.

04:08.373 --> 04:09.791
It's horrible.

04:10.417 --> 04:11.543
(tense music)

04:22.471 --> 04:24.097
-GIBSON: Captain!
-CARRADINE: Why aren't
you upstairs?

04:24.097 --> 04:26.558
I was. But an incident occurred
with one of the passengers.

04:26.683 --> 04:29.102
-Take care of it.
-There's been a murder.

04:30.562 --> 04:33.357
♪Build it up
with iron and steel

04:33.357 --> 04:36.026
♪My fair lady♪

04:36.902 --> 04:38.195
Let's find the captain.

04:38.904 --> 04:42.032
But first, can you help me
out this bind?

04:42.157 --> 04:43.116
(high tempo music)

04:47.496 --> 04:51.625
GWEN: (softly) Where...is...she?

04:54.336 --> 04:56.797
(metal clangs)
(shackles drop)

04:59.883 --> 05:01.176
Thank you, Cassandra.

05:01.552 --> 05:05.180
(sniffs)
Daddy? My name is Jackie.

05:05.180 --> 05:06.682
(dramatic music)

05:13.021 --> 05:13.981
(Gwen staggered breath)

05:14.815 --> 05:17.734
(glass crunching)
GWEN: Where...is...she?

05:17.901 --> 05:20.195
(crew member screaming)

05:23.282 --> 05:24.241
(thump)

05:26.827 --> 05:27.870
(door bolt slides closed)

05:27.870 --> 05:28.829
(upbeat violin music)

05:49.057 --> 05:50.601
(music becomes threatening)
(dog barking)

05:50.601 --> 05:51.643
(siren blares)

05:51.643 --> 05:54.062
♪...he must go, he must go♪

05:55.063 --> 05:56.023
(siren blaring

05:57.983 --> 05:59.026
(door kicks)

05:59.026 --> 06:00.152
(children chanting)

06:05.032 --> 06:06.742
(treacherous music)

06:08.952 --> 06:10.120
JACKIE: No! No!

06:10.120 --> 06:11.538
(blood spatters)

06:14.583 --> 06:18.921
(people chattering)

06:18.921 --> 06:22.090
DAVID: Right, anyone asks,
we're Mr and Mrs William Howe.

06:22.424 --> 06:23.842
GWEN: Are you sure
they cancelled?

06:24.384 --> 06:25.802
-JACKIE: Who am I?
-DAVID: Our niece.

06:25.802 --> 06:28.055
GWEN: They might
just be delayed,
have you thought of that?

06:28.055 --> 06:30.140
DAVID: Stop worrying. Apparently
Mrs Howe's weak stomach

06:30.140 --> 06:31.266
caused her so much upset,

06:31.266 --> 06:32.768
she's still clinging
to a toilet bowl.

06:32.768 --> 06:34.436
JACKIE: Do I have to
use my real name?

06:34.436 --> 06:36.271
-DAVID: Why?
-Jackie is so boring!

06:36.605 --> 06:38.357
How about...Cassandra?

06:38.357 --> 06:39.483
DAVID: That's a terrible name.

06:39.483 --> 06:41.652
GWEN: I was fine in
third class dining.

06:42.069 --> 06:43.028
I wasn't.

06:43.570 --> 06:44.905
-Were you?
-Mm-hmm.

06:45.572 --> 06:47.282
Oh, what does
a seven-year-old know?

06:47.282 --> 06:48.784
-Eight!
-Really?

06:48.784 --> 06:50.244
GWEN: Have you any idea
what will happen

06:50.244 --> 06:52.412
if they catch us
impersonating other guests?

06:52.538 --> 06:53.497
(pen scratches)

06:55.541 --> 06:58.335
GUEST: Thank you.

06:58.335 --> 07:01.463
DAVID: We, err, reserved
a table.
The name is Howe.

07:01.463 --> 07:02.840
William Howe?

07:03.257 --> 07:05.092
Ah, yes. Er, you cancelled.

07:05.092 --> 07:06.677
Well, we're here now.

07:06.677 --> 07:08.262
That table is no longer
available.

07:09.304 --> 07:10.639
I'm sorry, Mr Howe.

07:11.473 --> 07:13.642
And it was for two guests, only.

07:13.642 --> 07:15.769
Captain...Howe.

07:16.353 --> 07:17.771
(clears throat)
-M'AITRE D: Army, Sir?

07:18.730 --> 07:21.275
Infantry. Northern Ireland.

07:21.275 --> 07:22.985
(battle sounds)

07:23.610 --> 07:24.987
Did you serve?

07:25.737 --> 07:28.240
Royal engineers. Palestine.

07:28.240 --> 07:29.741
(men laughing)

07:30.158 --> 07:32.077
DAVID: Oh, bugger.

07:33.287 --> 07:34.538
Blasted lighter.

07:34.538 --> 07:36.498
Could have sworn I brought it
with me.

07:37.374 --> 07:38.332
(lighter clicks)

07:38.959 --> 07:40.377
(exhales)

07:41.837 --> 07:43.005
(cigarette tip sizzles)

07:45.716 --> 07:48.760
Well...Captain Howe.

07:49.386 --> 07:51.388
-(exhales)
-Shall we see about that table?

07:51.388 --> 07:53.015
(jazz music playing)

07:55.642 --> 07:57.060
Happy Halloween!

07:57.060 --> 07:59.730
And boy, oh, boy, have
we got a show
or you tonight!

07:59.730 --> 08:01.607
So, come and join us
on the dance floor

08:01.607 --> 08:03.692
and let's 'raise some spirits'!

08:03.692 --> 08:04.943
(people chattering)

08:16.079 --> 08:17.331
This is you, Sir.

08:17.331 --> 08:21.668
Ah, perhaps you have something
a little more...

08:22.085 --> 08:24.296
central, for an old army pal?

08:24.296 --> 08:26.006
VIKTOR: My usual table.

08:32.471 --> 08:33.722
(Viktor groans)

08:34.139 --> 08:36.390
Reserved, I'm afraid.

08:37.726 --> 08:39.269
Typical army engineer.

08:40.020 --> 08:42.481
Technically correct,
but of no use to anyone.

08:42.981 --> 08:44.358
Enjoy your evening, Sir.

08:44.358 --> 08:45.651
Oh, fuck off.

08:45.651 --> 08:47.402
GWEN: Darling, please.

08:47.945 --> 08:49.238
This is fine.

08:49.530 --> 08:51.156
He's a movie producer.

08:51.156 --> 08:53.659
Made the one about a couple who
have a child out of wedlock,

08:53.659 --> 08:55.661
with hilarious consequences.

08:55.661 --> 08:58.288
-GWEN: One Up, One Down?
-(chuckles) Yeah, yeah.
Quite liked it.

08:58.789 --> 09:01.041
Heard he was in London
making a picture
with Fred Astaire.

09:01.041 --> 09:02.000
Really?

09:02.751 --> 09:04.253
I should go over
and introduce myself.

09:04.253 --> 09:05.212
-No.
-No.

09:05.212 --> 09:06.255
JACKIE: You always say,

09:06.255 --> 09:08.590
"If an opportunity comes along,
grab it."

09:08.590 --> 09:10.425
Yeah, I do, but never beg.

09:10.425 --> 09:12.678
Opportunity is slippery.

09:12.678 --> 09:15.681
It's like trying to catch a fish
with bare hands.

09:15.681 --> 09:18.600
The trick is to wait
and let it come to you,

09:18.600 --> 09:20.185
then when it gets close...
(hand bangs table)

09:20.185 --> 09:21.812
...grab it!
(mirror shatters)

09:21.812 --> 09:23.230
(chuckles) And don't let it go,

09:23.230 --> 09:25.524
no matter how much it begs
and tries to slip away.

09:26.024 --> 09:27.317
Hold on tight.

09:28.527 --> 09:30.988
And don't be afraid
to get your hands dirty.

09:30.988 --> 09:32.573
How long must I wait?

09:32.573 --> 09:33.782
Haven't you heard?

09:34.241 --> 09:38.078
Patience is next to godliness.
(chuckles)

09:40.163 --> 09:43.667
♪Release me, release me
and stop haunting me

09:44.293 --> 09:46.920
DAVID: Right.
Who else needs a drink?

09:47.296 --> 09:48.881
-♪Release me♪
-Garon?

09:49.339 --> 09:50.424
♪Release me♪

09:53.594 --> 09:55.053
♪and stop haunting me♪

09:55.304 --> 09:57.139
-The quality of the work,
the quality...
-Mom...

09:57.139 --> 09:59.516
...the, the quality of the work
and the story you tell,

09:59.516 --> 10:00.809
that is all very important,

10:00.809 --> 10:03.645
but the, the truth of
the matter is...
-Mom.

10:04.313 --> 10:05.689
Um, yes. Yes?

10:05.689 --> 10:07.608
Why can't ghosts move on?

10:07.608 --> 10:08.609
Er, what does your book say?

10:09.193 --> 10:11.570
-Nothing.
-Well, it is a good question.

10:12.070 --> 10:14.531
The quality of the work,
and the story you tell...

10:14.531 --> 10:16.491
Dad should write about it
in his book.

10:16.867 --> 10:19.203
Er, I'm not sure that's
the angle they want to take.

10:19.912 --> 10:22.331
Well, then change his mind.

10:22.539 --> 10:25.501
Who wants to read about
boring old architecture

10:26.001 --> 10:27.503
on a haunted ship?
-(laughs)

10:27.503 --> 10:28.670
What?

10:29.213 --> 10:31.298
Um, well, maybe we
should leave it

10:31.298 --> 10:33.008
for the people in
charge to decide.

10:33.008 --> 10:34.176
I hope they say yes.

10:35.177 --> 10:37.304
It's been ages since the three
of us did anything.

10:37.304 --> 10:39.598
Yep.
Feels that way.

10:39.598 --> 10:41.266
He might as well
live in a different country.

10:41.266 --> 10:42.976
Well, it's kind of appropriate,
then,

10:42.976 --> 10:46.104
that we are meeting on a ship
that has travelled
the whole world.

10:46.104 --> 10:49.399
-Or a different continent.
-Honey, you're being
a little dramatic.

10:49.775 --> 10:51.026
You just needed time
to settle in.

10:51.026 --> 10:53.695
You know, new home,
new school, new friends.

10:53.695 --> 10:55.447
-Yeah, right.
-What?

10:57.199 --> 10:58.617
-Nothing.
-I told you,

10:58.617 --> 10:59.910
those kids don't know
what they're talking about.

10:59.910 --> 11:01.078
That is why they're kids.

11:02.329 --> 11:03.664
Do you believe them?

11:04.331 --> 11:06.375
Then you are just as stupid
as they are.

11:06.583 --> 11:09.461
-No, I'm not!
No, you're not. You're not.

11:11.547 --> 11:12.756
(exhales)

11:13.423 --> 11:17.386
(game plays)
A sailor went to...

11:17.719 --> 11:19.179
♪sea, sea, sea...♪

11:19.972 --> 11:22.099
♪to see what he could...♪

11:23.183 --> 11:24.393
♪...see, see, see♪

11:24.518 --> 11:25.853
I'm not four.

11:25.978 --> 11:27.062
Right.

11:27.980 --> 11:30.274
♪But all that he could
see, see, see...

11:31.316 --> 11:34.361
♪was the bottom of the
deep blue sea, sea, sea

11:35.779 --> 11:39.449
♪Two sailors went to
sea, sea, sea

11:39.658 --> 11:43.328
♪To see what they could
see, see, see

11:43.579 --> 11:47.165
♪And all that they could
see, see, see

11:47.374 --> 11:51.670
♪Was the bottom of the
deep blue sea, sea, sea

11:51.670 --> 11:52.880
(dramatic music)

12:01.513 --> 12:02.848
(camera housing clicks closed)

12:03.515 --> 12:04.683
Okay.

12:05.309 --> 12:07.436
Go do some of that
ghost hunting, honey.

12:17.738 --> 12:19.114
(camera clicks)

12:25.996 --> 12:27.122
(exhales)

12:27.122 --> 12:28.081
(dramatic music)

12:43.263 --> 12:44.681
(film reel static)

12:47.184 --> 12:48.644
REPORTER:
For thirty-one years,

12:48.644 --> 12:51.563
the Queen Mary served
as a majestic city of the sea.

12:51.980 --> 12:54.775
Now she's dropped anchor
for the final time.

12:54.775 --> 12:56.193
Closing out a career

12:56.193 --> 12:59.488
unequalled in the history of
commercial sea voyaging.

12:59.488 --> 13:01.532
A career that took her
through a depression,

13:01.532 --> 13:05.035
a world war,
a period of unequalled glory,

13:05.035 --> 13:06.787
and a last great voyage.

13:06.787 --> 13:09.373
CAPTAIN:Well, I would describe
this Queen Mary's
the most elegant

13:09.373 --> 13:12.751
and the finest ship that has
ever sailed any of the oceans.

13:12.751 --> 13:15.128
CREW MEMBER:The saddest
thing is,
I think, to ever happen

13:15.128 --> 13:18.590
because this has got to
be one of the most
beautiful ships that was, er...

13:18.590 --> 13:19.967
anyone's ever built.

13:19.967 --> 13:21.635
(jazz music)

13:21.635 --> 13:24.304
MAN:We feel that The Queen Mary
will be sort of

13:24.304 --> 13:27.307
the crown jewel in what
we hope will be

13:27.307 --> 13:32.104
the foremost water recreation
development in the entire
United States.

13:32.104 --> 13:35.315
MAN:Their predictions
are as high as
two and a half million
people a year

13:35.315 --> 13:40.070
will be coming down
to visit and board
The Queen Mary for its
various activities.

13:42.614 --> 13:46.910
PATRICK: The quality of the work
and the story that you
tell, the pictures,

13:46.910 --> 13:49.997
that's all very...quality,
the quality...

13:50.706 --> 13:52.915
-Dad! Dad!
-Hey, son!

13:53.750 --> 13:55.043
I have missed you.

13:55.043 --> 13:56.170
(chuckles) Me too!

13:56.837 --> 13:59.965
-Hi, Patrick.
-Hey...Anne.

14:00.382 --> 14:01.550
Glad you made it,

14:01.758 --> 14:03.302
although you are a little late,
but that's fine.

14:03.302 --> 14:05.095
-Sorry.
-I rung ahead, let them know.

14:05.262 --> 14:06.722
You wanna go through it again,
or...?

14:07.222 --> 14:08.265
-The pitch?
-Yeah.

14:08.974 --> 14:10.475
Um, I'm good if you are?

14:10.475 --> 14:13.187
I'm, I'm good.
-Er, well, although, er...

14:13.478 --> 14:16.982
the publisher thinks a more
holistic approach is needed.

14:17.441 --> 14:22.779
Um, books, website, 3D tour?

14:23.614 --> 14:24.823
TOUR GUIDE: Guests have reported
(camera shutter clicks)

14:24.823 --> 14:26.575
seeing a woman in white,
playing piano.

14:26.575 --> 14:29.036
A war bride, who,
after learning her husband died

14:29.036 --> 14:31.455
serving in France,
took her own life.

14:32.206 --> 14:35.209
You can pick up a
limited-edition
doll
of the woman in white

14:35.209 --> 14:37.044
in the gift shop
on your way out.

14:37.336 --> 14:41.131
Next, we'll see where
Fred Astaire
once danced the cha cha.

14:41.131 --> 14:44.384
I'm half expecting Fred Astaire
to jump out and try
sell me a hoover.

14:44.384 --> 14:46.678
-So, what's this
about a 3D tour?
-Oh, sorry.

14:47.137 --> 14:49.056
Er, you know, I just thought
you could mention it to him.

14:49.056 --> 14:50.724
PATRICK: It, it's a
big thing to just
mention.

14:50.724 --> 14:51.725
There are no visuals,
no concept work.

14:51.850 --> 14:53.727
Besides we've been
through this...
-Hey, uh...

14:53.727 --> 14:55.312
-...the ship's almost
80 years old.
-Hey, Dad.

14:55.312 --> 14:56.772
-PATRICK: It deserves
something...
-I'm thirsty.

14:56.772 --> 14:58.273
...you can feel and touch.
Something that lasts.

14:58.273 --> 14:59.358
-Can I get a frappe?
-PATRICK: Er, sure.

14:59.358 --> 15:00.692
ANNE: No, honey.
Who lets a kid drink coffee?

15:00.692 --> 15:02.194
-Oh, come on!
-PATRICK: Fine.

15:02.194 --> 15:03.362
ANNE: Hang on,
I'll give you water.

15:03.362 --> 15:04.321
LUKAS: Oh, forget it.

15:04.446 --> 15:05.656
With or without all this.

15:06.156 --> 15:07.366
But, er, you don't agree?

15:07.366 --> 15:09.660
No, I do, I do.
I think you're incredibly noble.

15:09.660 --> 15:11.286
-Well, thank you.
-And righteous.

15:11.286 --> 15:12.913
-Yeah, keep going.
-And have amazing intentions.

15:12.913 --> 15:14.957
I feel like the idea
is a little dated.

15:15.082 --> 15:16.291
I don't know what a book
is gonna do

15:16.291 --> 15:17.584
to save The Queen Mary.

15:17.668 --> 15:19.461
HOMELESS MAN: Get your God damn
freaking hands off me!

15:20.128 --> 15:21.797
(homeless man groans)

15:23.090 --> 15:25.092
If I catch you sneaking
in here one more time,

15:25.092 --> 15:27.302
I swear to God,
I'll crack your head open.

15:27.302 --> 15:28.971
PATRICK: So, I've been published
three times.

15:28.971 --> 15:30.889
ANNE: Oh, we're counting
academic papers now?

15:30.889 --> 15:32.474
PATRICK: All warmly received.

15:32.474 --> 15:33.934
(Anne and Patrick chatter)

15:33.934 --> 15:35.352
(tense music)

15:37.729 --> 15:39.481
Welcome to L.A.

15:39.481 --> 15:40.774
These days.

15:40.983 --> 15:42.651
So, what do you think?

15:42.651 --> 15:44.820
ANNE: Look, isn't
the real reason
you wanted to work on this...

15:44.820 --> 15:46.405
so you can spend time with...

15:48.824 --> 15:49.992
-PATRICK: Hey, buddy.
-(gasps)

15:49.992 --> 15:51.493
Huh? Yeah?

15:52.286 --> 15:54.955
