a doorway for the dead. (laughs)

25:57.391 --> 26:00.227
And although we're famous
for our fiction,

26:00.227 --> 26:03.021
you know, sometimes facts
can be much stranger.

26:03.021 --> 26:05.148
(tense music)

26:05.148 --> 26:10.737
Did you know in 1942, while, er,
transporting German and
Italian prisoners,

26:11.113 --> 26:13.615
she collided with one of our own
escort ships?

26:13.782 --> 26:18.453
Sank it.
Killing all but 99 of
its 400 sailors.

26:19.079 --> 26:23.375
And she just continued on
with little more than a scratch.

26:23.375 --> 26:24.501
(laughs)

26:24.626 --> 26:26.128
Would you take me on a tour?

26:27.337 --> 26:28.297
(clock chimes)

26:30.549 --> 26:31.508
(slow footsteps)

26:36.180 --> 26:37.639
(exhales)
Beautiful.

26:37.639 --> 26:40.684
Oh, yes, we have exactly
five hundred and ninety-six
working clocks

26:40.684 --> 26:41.727
aboard The Queen Mary.

26:41.727 --> 26:44.479
Wow. Really is a time
machine in here.

26:45.564 --> 26:47.649
We should definitely get
all these details in the book.

26:47.649 --> 26:50.068
Well, the Queen's Salon
was a social hub at night.

26:50.068 --> 26:51.653
Winston Churchill used
to sit over there,

26:51.653 --> 26:53.655
Alfred Hitchcock drank
his martini there,

26:53.655 --> 26:55.699
and Bob Hope wrote his
column over there.

26:56.116 --> 26:57.492
Tourists, they love that.

26:57.492 --> 26:59.745
You know, knowing what
famous people did,

26:59.995 --> 27:00.954
where they went.

27:01.079 --> 27:02.789
Is there anything else
you can show me?

27:03.582 --> 27:05.292
(camera shutter clicking)

27:08.754 --> 27:09.880
(bulb flashes)

27:13.509 --> 27:14.885
(loud footsteps, spurs jangling)

27:15.219 --> 27:16.053
(tense music)

27:28.857 --> 27:29.691
(Lukas panicking)

27:33.987 --> 27:35.447
(camera shutter clicks)

27:37.241 --> 27:39.576
